<node TEXT="threading" ID="ID_149062990" CREATED="1277697954897" MODIFIED="1277697954897">
<node TEXT="If you&apos;re running Jitter, it&apos;s important to know that Jitter processing typically takes place in the UI thread," ID="ID_304361490" CREATED="1277697954897" MODIFIED="1277697954897"/>
<node TEXT="three threads" ID="ID_93907864" CREATED="1277697954897" MODIFIED="1277697954897">
<node TEXT="There are three parts of MaxMSP that can potentially run in their own threads. Audio code and UI tasks run in their own threads, so it is possible that OS X or XP can move the audio to the second processor while the UI remains on the first. The MaxMSP scheduler can be set so that it either runs in its own thread, or run in either the audio or UI task threads using the DSP Status window (found in the Options menu):" ID="ID_1584170783" CREATED="1277697954897" MODIFIED="1277697954897"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="three choices" ID="ID_984425000" CREATED="1277697954897" MODIFIED="1277697954897">
<node TEXT="* If &quot;Max Scheduler in Overdrive&quot; is off, the scheduler will run in the same thread as UI tasks." ID="ID_134559721" CREATED="1277697954897" MODIFIED="1277697954897"/>
<node TEXT="* If &quot;Max Scheduler in Overdrive&quot; is on AND &quot;Scheduler in Audio Interrupt&quot; is on, the scheduler will run in the same thread as the audio code." ID="ID_1715069563" CREATED="1277697954897" MODIFIED="1277697954897"/>
<node TEXT="* If &quot;Max Scheduler in Overdrive&quot; is on and &quot;Scheduler in Audio Interrupt&quot; is off, the scheduler will run in its own thread." ID="ID_168476112" CREATED="1277697954897" MODIFIED="1277697954897"/>
</node>
</node>
